This paper deals with optimization problems related to scheduling and resource allocation, which are typically studied in the areas of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), game theory (cs.GT), machine learning (cs.LG), and information theory (cs.IT). The focus on flow-time minimization in the unrelated machines setting suggests that the paper is more likely to be classified under cs.DS and cs.DM, which are sub-categories that cover topics such as scheduling algorithms, approximation algorithms, and combinatorial optimization. However, the use of approximation algorithms and the consideration of quality of service measures may also make cs.LG and cs.IT relevant. Finally, the mention of poly-logarithmic guarantees suggests that the paper may be of interest to researchers working on the design and analysis of algorithms for large-scale systems, which is a topic that spans multiple sub-categories in computer science.
